Mike
There is a difference.  My understanding is that PGP is a completed
operational system (ala "PGP 2.2 Key available via finger").  I havn't
seen the "Moby Crypto" package but "heard" it had all the essential
features short of being compiled.  I expect one of the Govt's questions
might  follow " Mr. Ward, have you ever compiled the source code in
question".  I'd bet lunch the true answer is affirmative.

>>Anyone "reasonably skilled in the art", and many kids, can compile said
>>in seconds into executables (make a key, attach a bayonet lug).
>
>   Anybody reasonably skilled in the art can read Numerical Recipes in
>C, and Knuth, and construct some reasonably secure crypto (triple DES)
>using RSA for key exchange.

MIke
Possibly true for crude implementations.  There are more neuances than
most think.

That still doesn't make it "exportable by personal decleration or whim". 
"Anyone" didn't take the steps to put the essential system together. 
There is significantly more to a good secure system than linking DES and
RSA code.  

(ob_mode_on  Precisely one of the reasons the Net's "homebrew" Secure
Telephone won't fly anytime soon. No one has yet to ask questions in the
most difficult areas in Secure Telephony...They're hung up on V.42 vs
V.xx with / without compression, which is a relativly trivial issue. 
Best I can tell, no one commenting has any experience with existing
Secure Telephones.  ob_mode_off)

